                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Cincinnati Ohio</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>14<hi rend="sup">th</hi> December <hi rend="sup"
                                                  >5609</hi>/<hi rend="sub">1848</hi></date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Revd Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">I have read attentively and with much satisfaction<lb/>
                                        <persName>Dr. Wise's</persName> address and your preliminary
                                        and appended remarks upon<lb/> it, inserted in the Occidents
                                        of this month. You have both spoken out<lb/> and truly
                                        represented the many existing circumstances that are any
                                        thing<lb/> but satisfactory to those who among us appreciate
                                        the religion we profess<lb/> and the great part our nation
                                        has been destined to fill in the Divine<lb/> economy. Unless
                                        our people are now what they were when reproached as<lb/> in
                                        Isaiah” Who is blind but my servant? Or deaf, as my
                                        messenger<lb/> that I sent? Who is blind as he that is
                                        perfect, and blind as the<lb/> Lord's servant? seeing many
                                        things, but thou observest not: opening<lb/> the ears, but
                                        he heareth not,” such appeals as yours &amp; <persName>Dr.
                                                  Wise's</persName><lb/> cannot fail to rouse them
                                        to a sense of what they owe to their God.—to<lb/> society
                                        and to themselves. Through <persName>Mr. Gutheime</persName>
                                        you will learn<lb/> those appeals have produced their effect
                                        here. several members of the<lb/> three congregations of
                                        this city met and adopted the resolutions he<lb/> forwards
                                        you, a copy of which is to be sent likewise to the Trustees
                                        of<lb/> each of the Synagogues. It is expected that the
                                        Trustees will jointly<lb/> convene a general meeting of
                                        their members and though the result<lb/> cannot be certainly
                                        predicted we cherish the hope that the meeting<lb/> will
                                        express their concurrence in the views taken by you &amp;
                                                  <persName>Dr Wise</persName></p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>and resolve on appointing agents to attend the meeting proposed
                                        by<lb/> you both: probably the congregations here may
                                        resolve to address<lb/> a circular to the several synagogues
                                        in the Union suggestive of<lb/> each adopting a similar
                                        course: Your meeting may then present<lb/> the imposing
                                        character of a representation of all or of such of the<lb/>
                                        congregations in these states as are disposed to consider
                                        the expediency<lb/> and utility of forming the Union in
                                        question. Should the Trustees<lb/> of the Synagogues here
                                        convene a general meeting and the result<lb/> prove such as
                                        we wish I will then forward you from time to time<lb/> some
                                        details upon the objects, effects &amp;c of such a union, in
                                        order<lb/> that being disseminated through the occident the
                                        great importance<lb/> of the measure and the numerous
                                        benefits that may be expected to<lb/> accrue from it to the
                                        whole community of Jews may be generally<lb/> perceived. I
                                        am reverend Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Yours truly</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">
                                        <persName role="author">A A. Lindo</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>
